I'm not privy enough to the proceedings of courts to say much for certain, but I think that scent would end up along the same lines as eyewitness testimony. Of course it would probably be much more common to have brought up due to it being something that sticks around for longer.
I also think they'd probably have a lot more physical contact. Partially because other animals are typically much more keen on physical communication than humans, but also because among any sort of group having your scent on the others and the others' scents on you would probably be a sign of trust, loyalty, and good relations. The type of sweat glands that animals typically use for communication, humans have all over our bodies. Among things that can be conveyed through scents, we'd probably be able to be read like an open book, or more accurately, a giant, flashing, neon billboard.
Scents would definitely play a big part in their societies and cultures. That's definitely another area where humans could be considered outsiders.
